        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 5:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and the lame man in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 3:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The command, which would have seemed a mockery to one who did not rise beyond the limits of experience, is obeyed by the will that had been inspired by the new power of faith. The natural inference from the special fact recorded in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 14:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is that the command was given in Greek, and therefore that St. Paul had taught in that language.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "And he leaped and walked.—The two verbs differ in their tense: he leaped, as with a single bound, and then continued walking. (Comp. Note on Acts 3:8.)",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "And he leaped and walked.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—The two verbs differ in their tense: he leaped, as with a single bound, and then continued walking. (Comp. Note on ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 3:8",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".)",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
