  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Gill's Exposition of the Entire Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Said with a loud voice,.... Not only that the man, but that all might hear and attend to the miracle about to be wrought: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "stand upright on thy feet; in five of Beza's manuscripts, and in other copies, and in the Complutensian edition, and in the Syriac version, this clause is introduced with these words, \"I say unto thee, in the name of the Lord Jesus Christ\"; which is much such a form that Peter used, Acts 3:6 whereby the virtue of the miracle is ascribed to Christ, and not assumed by the apostle: ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "stand upright on thy feet; in five of Beza's manuscripts, and in other copies, and in the Complutensian edition, and in the Syriac version, this clause is introduced with these words, \"I say unto thee, in the name of the Lord Jesus Christ\"; which is much such a form that Peter used, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 3:6",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " whereby the virtue of the miracle is ascribed to Christ, and not assumed by the apostle: ",
            "children": []
